```rust
fn merge_sort<T: Ord + Copy>(arr: &mut [T]) {
    let len = arr.len();
    if len <= 1 {
        return;
    }

    let mid = len / 2;
    merge_sort(&mut arr[..mid]);
    merge_sort(&mut arr[mid..]);

    let mut left_half = arr[..mid].to_vec();
    let mut right_half = arr[mid..].to_vec();
    left_half.push(std::marker::PhantomData);
    right_half.push(std::marker::PhantomData);

    let mut i = 0;
    let mut j = 0;

    for k in 0..len {
        if left_half[i] <= right_half[j] {
            arr[k] = left_half[i];
            i += 1;
        } else {
            arr[k] = right_half[j];
            j += 1;
        }
    }
}
```

Time Complexity:
- The merge sort algorithm divides the array into two halves recursively until each subarray contains only one element. This division step takes O(log n) time.
- During the merge step, the algorithm compares and merges the elements from the two sorted halves. This merging process takes O(n) time for each level of recursion.
- Therefore, the overall time complexity of merge sort is O(n log n) in all cases (worst, average, and best).

Space Complexity:
- Merge sort requires additional space to store the temporary arrays during the merging process.
- At each level of recursion, it creates two temporary arrays, each of size n/2.
- The maximum depth of recursion is O(log n), so the total space required is O(n) for the temporary arrays.
- Hence, the space complexity of merge sort is O(n).

