## Hardening Supabase App Against ReDoS Attacks

### 1. Input Validation
- Use built-in Postgres string functions instead of regular expressions whenever possible.
- Validate and sanitize user input before processing it in your Supabase database functions and triggers.

```sql
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION validate_email(email text)
RETURNS BOOLEAN AS $$
BEGIN
  RETURN email ~* '^[A-Za-z0-9._%+-]+@[A-Za-z0-9.-]+[.][A-Za-z]+$';
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql IMMUTABLE;
```

### 2. Rate Limiting
- Implement rate limiting on your Supabase app's API endpoints to prevent abuse.
- Use a reverse proxy or API gateway that supports rate limiting, such as Nginx or Kong.

```nginx
http {
    limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=mylimit:10m rate=5r/s;

    server {
        location /api/ {
            limit_req zone=mylimit burst=10;
            proxy_pass http://localhost:3000;
        }
    }
}
```

### 3. Secure Regular Expressions
- Avoid using complex regular expressions that are prone to ReDoS.
- Use atomic groups and possessive quantifiers to prevent excessive backtracking.

```sql
-- Insecure regular expression
SELECT * FROM users WHERE name ~* '(a+)+b';

-- Secure regular expression using atomic groups
SELECT * FROM users WHERE name ~* '(?>a+)++b';
```

By implementing these techniques, you can significantly reduce the risk of ReDoS attacks on your Supabase app. Always keep your dependencies up to date and monitor your app for any suspicious activity.```

