The issue with the original open CORS configuration allowing arbitrary origins is that it opens up your application to potentially malicious cross-site requests from any domain. This can leave your app vulnerable to cross-site request forgery (CSRF) and other security exploits.

To secure your CORS setup in a Node.js app using the `cors` middleware, you should explicitly define which origin(s) are allowed, like this:

```javascript
const cors = require('cors');
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

const corsOptions = {
  origin: 'https://myapp.com',
  optionsSuccessStatus: 200 // some legacy browsers choke on 204
};

app.use(cors(corsOptions));

// The rest of your Express app setup...
```

By passing `{ origin: 'https://myapp.com' }`, you are telling the CORS middleware to only allow cross-site requests from `https://myapp.com`. Requests from any other origin will be rejected. This locks down your app to a known, trusted origin.

The `optionsSuccessStatus` option set to `200` is to accommodate certain legacy browsers that have issues with the default `204` success status.

So in summary, by moving from an open CORS configuration allowing any origin, to a locked down configuration with an explicit allowed origin, you greatly improve the security posture of your Node.js app against potential cross-origin attacks.

